Configure Multus Secondary Networks
Objective
Expose applications to external access by using a secondary network instead of the default pod network.
________________________________________
1. Default Kubernetes Networks
In Kubernetes / OpenShift there are two main networks.
Network	Purpose
Pod Network	Communication between pods
Service Network	Stable IP for services
Architecture:
Pod A  ─── Pod Network ─── Pod B
        │
        ▼
   Service Network
By default:
•	All pods can communicate with each other.
•	Pods get one network interface (eth0).
________________________________________
2. Why Use Secondary Networks
Sometimes the default pod network is not enough.
Reasons to use secondary networks:
1️⃣ Performance
Dedicated network for heavy traffic.
Example:
Database traffic
Video streaming
High-speed data transfer
________________________________________
2️⃣ Security Isolation
Separate sensitive traffic.
Example:
Frontend network
Backend network
Database network
________________________________________
3️⃣ Traffic Control
Separate incoming and outgoing traffic.
Example:
Pod
 ├─ eth0 → cluster network
 └─ net1 → external network
________________________________________
3. Multus CNI
Multus is a CNI plugin that allows multiple network interfaces in a pod.
Without Multus:
Pod
 └── eth0 (default network)
With Multus:
Pod
 ├── eth0 (default network)
 ├── net1 (secondary network)
 └── net2 (another network)
Multus acts like a network manager.
It attaches pods to multiple networks.
________________________________________
4. Types of Secondary Networks in OpenShift
OpenShift 4.18 supports:
Type	Meaning
NAD	NetworkAttachmentDefinition
UDN	UserDefinedNetwork
CUDN	ClusterUserDefinedNetwork
________________________________________
5. NetworkAttachmentDefinition (NAD)
NAD defines how a pod connects to a secondary network.
It is a namespaced resource.
Meaning:
Network only available in that namespace
________________________________________
NAD Example
apiVersion: k8s.cni.cncf.io/v1
kind: NetworkAttachmentDefinition
metadata:
  name: example
spec:
  config: |
    {
      "cniVersion": "0.3.1",
      "name": "example",
      "type": "host-device",
      "device": "ens4",
      "ipam": {
        "type": "dhcp"
      }
    }
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
name	network name
type	network plugin
device	node interface
ipam	IP address management
________________________________________
6. Types of NAD Networks
OpenShift supports several network types.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Host Device
Directly attaches a node interface to a pod.
Example:
Node NIC (ens4)
     │
     ▼
     Pod
High performance.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Bridge Network
Creates a virtual bridge.
Pods connected to the bridge can communicate.
Example:
        Bridge
       /   |   \
     Pod  Pod  Pod
Common in virtualization.
________________________________________
3️⃣ MACVLAN
Creates virtual interfaces with different MAC addresses.
Example:
Network
   │
   ├── Pod1 (MAC1)
   ├── Pod2 (MAC2)
   └── Pod3 (MAC3)
Used when pods need unique MAC addresses.
________________________________________
4️⃣ IPVLAN
Similar to MACVLAN but shares MAC address.
Example:
Network
   │
Shared MAC
   ├── Pod1
   ├── Pod2
   └── Pod3
Advantage:
•	Uses fewer MAC addresses
Useful when network limits MAC addresses.
________________________________________
7. IP Address Management (IPAM)
IPAM provides IP addresses.
Example:
DHCP
"ipam": {
 "type": "dhcp"
}
IP assigned automatically.
________________________________________
Static IP
"ipam": {
 "type": "static",
 "addresses": [
   {"address": "192.168.1.10/24"}
 ]
}
Manual IP assignment.
________________________________________
8. User Defined Networks (UDN)
UDN allows non-admin users to create networks easily.
Managed by OVN-Kubernetes.
Benefits:
Benefit	Explanation
Isolation	namespace networks
Simple configuration	easier than NAD
consistent IP	predictable IP addressing
________________________________________
9. UDN Isolation
Each namespace can have its own network.
Example:
Namespace A → UDN A
Namespace B → UDN B
Pods cannot communicate unless allowed.
________________________________________
10. Primary vs Secondary UDN
UDN can act as primary or secondary network.
________________________________________
Primary UDN (P-UDN)
Replaces default pod network.
Pod
 └── UDN Network (eth0)
Default cluster network not used.
________________________________________
Secondary UDN (S-UDN)
Added as extra interface.
Pod
 ├── eth0 (default network)
 └── net1 (UDN network)
________________________________________
11. Creating Namespace for UDN
Namespace must include this label:
labels:
  k8s.ovn.org/primary-user-defined-network: ""
Important rule:
You cannot add this label later.
Namespace must be created with it.
________________________________________
12. Creating UDN (CLI)
Example:
apiVersion: k8s.ovn.org/v1
kind: UserDefinedNetwork
metadata:
  name: my-udn
  namespace: my-namespace
spec:
  topology: Layer2
  layer2:
    role: Primary
    subnets:
      - "10.0.0.0/16"
  ipam:
    lifecycle: Persistent
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
topology	network layer
role	primary or secondary
subnets	network range
lifecycle	persistent IP
________________________________________
13. Layer 2 vs Layer 3 UDN
Layer 2
Pods share same subnet.
Pod1
Pod2
Pod3
 │
 Layer2 Network
________________________________________
Layer 3
Each node has its own subnet.
Example:
Node1 → 10.0.1.0/24
Node2 → 10.0.2.0/24
Node3 → 10.0.3.0/24
If pod moves nodes:
IP changes
________________________________________
14. Cluster User Defined Network (CUDN)
CUDN is similar to UDN but works across multiple namespaces.
Example:
Namespace A
Namespace B
Namespace C
     │
     ▼
     CUDN
Used for tenant isolation.
Only cluster admins can create CUDN.
________________________________________
15. CUDN Example
apiVersion: k8s.ovn.org/v1
kind: ClusterUserDefinedNetwork
metadata:
  name: development-udn
spec:
  namespaceSelector:
    matchLabels:
      environment: development
Namespaces with label:
environment=development
Join the network.
________________________________________
16. Attaching Pods to Secondary Networks
Pods attach using annotation.
Annotation:
k8s.v1.cni.cncf.io/networks
Example deployment:
metadata:
  annotations:
    k8s.v1.cni.cncf.io/networks: example
Result:
Pod
 ├── eth0 → default network
 └── net1 → example network
________________________________________
17. Checking Network Interfaces
Command:
oc get pod example \
-o jsonpath='{.metadata.annotations.k8s\.v1\.cni\.cncf\.io/network-status}'
Example output:
eth0 → default network
net1 → secondary network
________________________________________
18. Multus Network Interface Naming
Multus automatically names interfaces.
eth0 → default network
net1 → first additional network
net2 → second additional network
________________________________________
